SIMPLE: trammel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trammel
<hw>Tram"mel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>tramail</ets>, <ets>tr⟦eacute⟧mail</ets>, a net, LL.
<ets>tremaculum</ets>, <ets>tremacle</ets>, a kind of net for taking
fish; L. <ets>tres</ets> three + <ets>macula</ets> a mesh. See
<er>Three</er>, and <er>Mail</er> armor.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind
of net for catching birds, fishes, or other prey.</def>
<rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A net for confining a woman's hair.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of shackle used for regulating the motions of
a horse and making him amble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: Whatever impedes activity, progress, or
freedom, as a net or shackle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] disdain the <qex>trammels</qex> of any sordid contract.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An iron hook of various forms and sizes, used for
handing kettles and other vessels over the fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An instrument for
drawing ellipses, one part of which consists of a cross with two grooves
at right angles to each other, the other being a beam carrying two pins
(which slide in those grooves), and also the describing pencil.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A beam compass. See under <er>Beam</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trammel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trammel
<hw>Tram"mel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trammeled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or
<conjf>Trammelled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trammeling</conjf>, or <conjf>Trammelling</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To entangle, as in a net; to catch.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To confine; to hamper; to shackle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trammeled</ent>⟦br⟧
